1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,420
 Now I want to talk a little bit about a concept,

2
00:00:02,420 --> 00:00:03,440
 ModelViewController.

3
00:00:03,440 --> 00:00:06,360
 It's not super essential to understanding

4
00:00:06,360 --> 00:00:09,120
 how everything works in web servers,

5
00:00:09,120 --> 00:00:10,960
 but it's a great set of terminology

6
00:00:10,960 --> 00:00:13,720
 that we use among web developers.

7
00:00:13,720 --> 00:00:17,200
 And I think as you move into your role as a web developer,

8
00:00:17,200 --> 00:00:18,680
 you ought to understand this.

9
00:00:18,680 --> 00:00:21,280
 So this is a picture of the request-response cycle.

10
00:00:21,280 --> 00:00:23,200
 At the bottom we have the browser,

11
00:00:23,200 --> 00:00:26,200
 and at the top we have a web server talking on port 80.

12
00:00:26,200 --> 00:00:29,520
 The user clicks on a page, clicks on a link,

13
00:00:29,520 --> 00:00:31,600
 the browser intercepts that link,

14
00:00:31,600 --> 00:00:33,560
 opens a connection up to the web server,

15
00:00:33,560 --> 00:00:36,560
 sends a get request, the web server does its work,

16
00:00:36,560 --> 00:00:37,960
 and returns a web page.

17
00:00:37,960 --> 00:00:42,200
 And so that's sort of the basic request-response cycle.

18
00:00:42,200 --> 00:00:45,400
 And now we're going to, as in much of this class,

19
00:00:45,400 --> 00:00:47,440
 really expand what we're going to do

20
00:00:47,440 --> 00:00:49,120
 when we're in that web server.

21
00:00:49,120 --> 00:00:52,160
 So that's where we're going to take a look at this.

22
00:00:52,160 --> 00:00:56,600
 So basically ModelViewController is really a set of terms

23
00:00:56,600 --> 00:01:01,000
 that allow us to say this aspect,

24
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:03,480
 this part of the work that's going to be done

25
00:01:03,480 --> 00:01:06,000
 in the web server, it's either the model,

26
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:07,480
 it's the view or the controller.

27
00:01:07,480 --> 00:01:11,480
 And so the most value that it has is to say,

28
00:01:11,480 --> 00:01:14,160
 oh, that part right there, that's controller.

29
00:01:14,160 --> 00:01:16,800
 So ModelViewController is independent

30
00:01:16,800 --> 00:01:19,160
 of the programming language that you use,

31
00:01:19,160 --> 00:01:21,520
 independent of the operating system that you use.

32
00:01:21,520 --> 00:01:24,240
 It's pretty universal across the concept,

33
00:01:24,240 --> 00:01:28,880
 as an architecture, as a way of talking about web servers.

34
00:01:28,880 --> 00:01:32,880
 So the three parts of it, it'd be probably better

35
00:01:32,880 --> 00:01:34,800
 to call it ControllerViewModel,

36
00:01:34,800 --> 00:01:38,800
 or ModelControllerViewModel, or something like that.

37
00:01:38,800 --> 00:01:41,520
 But ModelViewController rolls off our tongue better.

38
00:01:41,520 --> 00:01:44,920
 So the definition, in my mind, of these terms

39
00:01:44,920 --> 00:01:49,000
 is the controller is this sort of abstract idea

40
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:52,960
 of what happens next, what is the sequence of events

41
00:01:52,960 --> 00:01:55,240
 that happen, and then where do we start from,

42
00:01:55,240 --> 00:01:57,320
 what do we do when we get a request,

43
00:01:57,320 --> 00:02:00,520
 and then afterwards, where do we go at the end of that.

44
00:02:00,520 --> 00:02:02,600
 The view is all the stuff we see.

45
00:02:02,600 --> 00:02:05,280
 It usually is at the end of the request response cycle,

46
00:02:05,280 --> 00:02:08,360
 we produce a view and we return the view back.

47
00:02:08,360 --> 00:02:11,520
 And one of the things that the request response cycle

48
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:14,440
 often does is either interacts by storing data

49
00:02:14,440 --> 00:02:16,800
 in a database, like an insert,

50
00:02:16,800 --> 00:02:19,760
 or it edits something and puts it in a database,

51
00:02:19,760 --> 00:02:21,880
 or it just reads stuff from the database

52
00:02:21,880 --> 00:02:25,480
 and shows it to us in the view.

53
00:02:25,480 --> 00:02:26,880
 And so that's called the model.

54
00:02:26,880 --> 00:02:30,000
 The database itself, and sort of the notion

55
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:33,280
 that we have persistent storage inside the application,

56
00:02:33,280 --> 00:02:34,680
 that's what we call the model.

57
00:02:34,680 --> 00:02:36,600
 The view is what we see, and the controller

58
00:02:36,600 --> 00:02:38,840
 is kind of the glue that puts it all together.

59
00:02:38,840 --> 00:02:41,960
 So the controller orchestrates all this stuff.

60
00:02:41,960 --> 00:02:45,120
 And so sometimes you don't say that's the controller,

61
00:02:45,120 --> 00:02:47,240
 but the controller is like several places

62
00:02:47,240 --> 00:02:50,240
 and the actual shape of your application.

63
00:02:51,680 --> 00:02:55,600
 So when we receive a request, we have a number of tasks

64
00:02:55,600 --> 00:02:58,600
 that we often have to do for each request.

65
00:02:58,600 --> 00:03:01,560
 Sometimes if it's like a form that's been sent to us,

66
00:03:01,560 --> 00:03:03,800
 we have some data that we have to receive,

67
00:03:03,800 --> 00:03:05,640
 validate and then process,

68
00:03:05,640 --> 00:03:07,480
 and then store it in a database maybe.

69
00:03:07,480 --> 00:03:10,600
 And so that's often thought of as the model work.

70
00:03:10,600 --> 00:03:13,240
 Then once we've done that, we make a decision,

71
00:03:13,240 --> 00:03:16,440
 like I've stored this, where do we want to send the user?

72
00:03:16,440 --> 00:03:17,680
 What do we want to show next?

73
00:03:17,680 --> 00:03:19,720
 What page to show next?

74
00:03:19,720 --> 00:03:22,160
 Maybe we show them a thank you page,

75
00:03:22,160 --> 00:03:24,360
 or maybe we send them back to the top page

76
00:03:24,360 --> 00:03:25,800
 of the application.

77
00:03:25,800 --> 00:03:29,120
 And so once we know what page we're gonna send back to them,

78
00:03:29,120 --> 00:03:30,680
 then that page has some data

79
00:03:30,680 --> 00:03:33,200
 that we might have to pull from the database.

80
00:03:33,200 --> 00:03:35,280
 And so we retrieve that using the model,

81
00:03:35,280 --> 00:03:37,960
 and then we produce, perhaps using a template,

82
00:03:37,960 --> 00:03:41,560
 some HTML response, and then put it back.

83
00:03:41,560 --> 00:03:45,160
 So these are the four typical steps that we break down.

84
00:03:45,160 --> 00:03:47,720
 Say, in comes an HTTP request.

85
00:03:47,720 --> 00:03:49,920
 First thing we do is if it has data that we're supposed

86
00:03:49,920 --> 00:03:52,000
 to do something with, we handle it,

87
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:54,840
 maybe store that data in a database.

88
00:03:54,840 --> 00:03:57,360
 Then we talk to the database and retrieve more data

89
00:03:57,360 --> 00:03:59,840
 to produce the next output that we're gonna make.

90
00:03:59,840 --> 00:04:03,560
 And then we produce the HTML or the other form of output,

91
00:04:03,560 --> 00:04:06,440
 and we send it back to the browser.

92
00:04:06,440 --> 00:04:10,120
 And so if we take a look at this in our Django application,

93
00:04:10,120 --> 00:04:13,520
 the Django application is pretty much

94
00:04:13,520 --> 00:04:16,320
 a model view controller application

95
00:04:16,320 --> 00:04:21,240
 in that the routing is very much the controller.

96
00:04:21,240 --> 00:04:25,960
 It is that which we, it's like, here comes a URL,

97
00:04:25,960 --> 00:04:28,720
 it's a request for something, where do we go?

98
00:04:28,720 --> 00:04:30,840
 And so when you write urls.py,

99
00:04:30,840 --> 00:04:32,480
 you're informing the controller.

100
00:04:32,480 --> 00:04:36,600
 So the urls.py I would say is part of the controller action,

101
00:04:36,600 --> 00:04:38,000
 the controller activity.

102
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:42,040
 The views is named the view.

103
00:04:42,040 --> 00:04:44,880
 So the view is a little bit controller

104
00:04:44,880 --> 00:04:47,600
 in that sometimes the view is storing some data

105
00:04:47,600 --> 00:04:50,720
 in the database, sometimes that's the job of the view.

106
00:04:50,720 --> 00:04:53,560
 Here comes some data before the view produces

107
00:04:53,560 --> 00:04:55,640
 the next output.

108
00:04:55,640 --> 00:04:59,200
 It actually has to store what came in on this request.

109
00:04:59,200 --> 00:05:02,000
 And then the view will do some controller activity,

110
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:04,520
 like it might decide, you know, I don't want you,

111
00:05:04,520 --> 00:05:07,120
 this is the wrong page now that we've processed your data.

112
00:05:07,120 --> 00:05:09,320
 I'm just gonna send you over to some other page.

113
00:05:09,320 --> 00:05:11,200
 That's kind of controller activity.

114
00:05:11,200 --> 00:05:13,400
 So it might say, I'll store the data.

115
00:05:13,400 --> 00:05:15,880
 It might, let's see here, can I, yeah.

116
00:05:15,880 --> 00:05:18,080
 So it might say, you know, here I go,

117
00:05:18,080 --> 00:05:19,560
 I'm gonna store some data,

118
00:05:19,560 --> 00:05:21,160
 and then I'm actually just gonna send you

119
00:05:21,160 --> 00:05:22,000
 to a different place.

120
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:24,120
 So I'm not even gonna give you an HTML.

121
00:05:24,120 --> 00:05:25,680
 And we'll talk about that redirect,

122
00:05:25,680 --> 00:05:28,040
 that's called a redirect in a bit.

123
00:05:28,040 --> 00:05:30,400
 Sometimes there is no data,

124
00:05:30,400 --> 00:05:32,240
 and so sometimes you get some data,

125
00:05:32,240 --> 00:05:33,880
 you route it to the right view,

126
00:05:33,880 --> 00:05:37,280
 and maybe some data has to be retrieved from the database,

127
00:05:37,280 --> 00:05:40,840
 merged together, and result is processed.

128
00:05:40,840 --> 00:05:43,840
 So when we think of views.py,

129
00:05:43,840 --> 00:05:48,840
 that is to me, both the controller and the view production.

130
00:05:48,840 --> 00:05:52,720
 So sometimes it's making decisions about where to go next.

131
00:05:52,720 --> 00:05:55,000
 Sometimes it's just handling incoming data

132
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:57,160
 or sending data out.

133
00:05:57,160 --> 00:06:02,160
 And similarly, the models is taken from model view controller

134
00:06:02,160 --> 00:06:07,320
 because the models.py is where we basically

135
00:06:07,320 --> 00:06:09,200
 do all the work to talk to the database,

136
00:06:09,200 --> 00:06:11,360
 whether it is storing stuff in the database

137
00:06:11,360 --> 00:06:12,840
 or retrieving stuff in the database.

138
00:06:12,840 --> 00:06:15,800
 We use the Django model capability

139
00:06:15,800 --> 00:06:20,200
 to implement the concept in model view controller of models.

140
00:06:20,200 --> 00:06:22,480
 So just a quick summary.

141
00:06:22,480 --> 00:06:25,040
 I like to think of urls.py,

142
00:06:25,040 --> 00:06:27,960
 and some of the views.py is the controller.

143
00:06:27,960 --> 00:06:29,600
 The models, of course, is all the things

144
00:06:29,600 --> 00:06:30,920
 that talk to the database.

145
00:06:30,920 --> 00:06:34,640
 And then the views are like the second half of views.py.

146
00:06:34,640 --> 00:06:37,800
 So produce using templates and forms.py,

147
00:06:37,800 --> 00:06:40,080
 and et cetera, et cetera, to produce the output

148
00:06:40,080 --> 00:06:41,080
 and send it out.

149
00:06:41,080 --> 00:06:44,560
 And so that's how I map the model view controller

150
00:06:44,560 --> 00:06:46,600
 onto the Django architecture.

151
00:06:46,600 --> 00:06:49,560
 And again, Django architecture was probably inspired

152
00:06:49,560 --> 00:06:50,680
 by the model view controller,

153
00:06:50,680 --> 00:06:52,920
 and that's why it takes some of its names

154
00:06:52,920 --> 00:06:54,640
 of some of its capabilities

155
00:06:54,640 --> 00:06:56,600
 from the model view controller concept.

156
00:06:56,600 --> 00:06:59,180
 (upbeat music)

